    <exercise id="fs-id2684892" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2681208">   
      <para id="import-auto-id1554680"><emphasis>Unreasonable Results</emphasis></para>
      <para id="fs-id1777590">(a) Assuming it is nonrelativistic, calculate the velocity of an electron with a 0.100-fm wavelength (small enough to detect details of a nucleus). (b) What is unreasonable about this result? (c) Which assumptions are unreasonable or inconsistent?</para>
    </problem>
<solution id="fs-id2700808">
    <para id="import-auto-id1304157">(a) <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>7.28</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>12</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{7 "." "28" times "10" rSup { size 8{"12"} } " m/s"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para><para id="import-auto-id1439234">(b) This is thousands of times the speed of light (an impossibility).</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id1359730">(c) The assumption that the electron is non-relativistic is unreasonable at this wavelength.</para>
    </solution>
